At the beginner level, it is usually better to learn these inside full phrases than as isolated dictionary meanings.

== Prepositions with pronouns

A preposition can also come before a pronoun:

- `met mij`
- `zonder jou`
- `bij ons`
- `van hem`

Examples:

- `Kom je met ons mee?`
- `Zij woont bij haar ouders.`
- `Ik krijg een bericht van hem.`

== Verb plus preposition

Some verbs regularly appear with a certain preposition. This is worth noticing early because the combination often feels fixed.

- `wachten op` -> `Ik wacht op de bus.`
- `denken aan` -> `Wij denken aan vakantie.`
- `houden van` -> `Hij houdt van muziek.`
- `praten over` -> `Zij praten over Nederlands.`

It is usually best to memorize the whole combination:

- not just `wachten`
- but `wachten op`

That will help you make more natural sentences later.

== A simple study habit

Take one noun and combine it with different prepositions:

- `Het boek ligt op de tafel.`
- `Het boek ligt in de tas.`
- `Het boek ligt onder de stoel.`

Then take one verb and do the same:

- `Ik ga naar school.`
- `Ik kom uit school.`
- `Ik praat over school.`

This kind of practice makes the meaning of each preposition much easier to feel.
